{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9d3a7221ec917b32", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                          AI_LectureNote: A Retrospective Pilot Study of a Post-ASR\n2\t                                          Workflow for English-Script Rendering and Semantic Drift in\n3\t                                                       Korean–English Medical Lectures\n4\t                                                               Kyeongeon Lee, Donghoon Chang, Seungryeol Baek,\n5\t                                                                         Taehong Kim, Wonjun Yang\n6\t                                                                     Sungkyunkwan University, Republic of Korea\n7\t                                                          boy.skier@g.skku.edu dhchang5765@gmail.com bsr20030507@g.skku.edu\n8\t                                                                        jinanara@skku.edu judereal15@gmail.com\n9\t\n10\t\n11\t\n12\t                                                                                        Abstract\n13\t                                                  AI_LectureNote is a historical, readability-oriented post-ASR workflow for Korean–\n14\t                                              English medical lectures. It rewrites speech-to-text output into study transcripts while\n15\t                                              restoring Latin-script medical terms rather than Korean phonetic transliterations. We ret-\n16\t                                              rospectively evaluate the workflow on four author-recorded lectures across five conditions.\n17\t                                              In this pilot, post-processing raised the macro English-script rendering rate from 0.39 to\n18\tarXiv:2607.17237v1 [cs.CL] 19 Jul 2026\n19\t\n20\t\n21\t\n22\t\n23\t                                              0.71 on the whisper-1 path and from 0.26 to 0.65 when applied to 3-minute chunked gpt-4o-\n24\t                                              transcribe output. However, English-script rendering did not imply semantic faithfulness:\n25\t                                              the two post-processed conditions showed semantic drift in 34 and 36 of 282 reference sen-\n26\t                                              tences and polarity failures in 11 and 13 of 101 polarity-cue rows. A descriptive cross-input\n27\t                                              comparison suggested different candidate failure patterns: polarity-failure sets overlapped\n28\t                                              more strongly across front-ends (Jaccard 0.60; 9 shared of 15 unioned failures) than general\n29\t                                              semantic-drift sets (Jaccard 0.23; 13 shared of 57 unioned drifts). This single-annotator pilot\n30\t                                              documents concrete failure modes rather than population rates and supports evaluating sur-\n31\t                                              face accuracy, term-script rendering, chunk-level script consistency, and medical-meaning\n32\t                                              preservation separately.\n33\t\n34\t\n35\t\n36\t                                         1. Introduction\n37\t                                         Students using recorded Korean–English medical lectures often need something different from\n38\t                                         a verbatim acoustic transcript. A useful study transcript should keep the lecturer’s medical\n39\t                                         claims readable, render English medical terminology in English script, and retain clinically or\n40\t                                         biologically important directionality. Generic ASR metrics do not directly measure this target.\n41\t                                         In Korean–English medical lectures, the gap is especially visible when ASR renders embedded\n42\t                                         English terms as Korean phonetic strings (for example, “carbonic anhydrase inhibitor” may\n43\t                                         be rendered as “카르보닉 아나이드레이즈 이니비터”), producing fluent-looking but hard-to-study\n44\t                                         transcripts.\n45\t                                            AI_LectureNote was built for that practical problem. It was a student-built prototype\n46\t                                         that used the OpenAI whisper-1 API as its raw ASR front-end and added domain-aware\n47\t                                         post-processing to restore medical terms and regularize wording into a study transcript. The\n48\t                                         system originated as an internal study aid. Here, we re-run that historical post-processing code\n49\t                                         unchanged and evaluate it retrospectively.\n50\t                                            The central distinction is between readability and faithfulness. English-script rendering\n51\t                                         makes a transcript easier to scan, search, and align with textbooks, but it can hide different\n52\t                                         errors. A rewritten transcript may replace a Korean phonetic string with an English medical\n53\t                                         word that looks plausible while being the wrong word. It may compress an explanation and\n54\t                                         drop the causal relation, or it may flip a polarity cue such as hypo- versus hyper-. These are\n55\t                                         not only formatting errors; they alter what a student would study.\n56\t\n57\t\n58\t                                                                                            1\n59\t\f   The motivating question is therefore not whether AI_LectureNote is a better ASR system\n60\tthan a modern commercial transcriber. The question is narrower: when readability-oriented\n61\tpost-ASR rewriting improves English-script rendering, what happens to medical-meaning faith-\n62\tfulness? This question remains relevant even with newer raw STT front-ends such as gpt-4o-\n63\ttranscribe, because fluent raw output and readable post-processed output can fail in different\n64\tways.\n65\t   We compare five conditions over the same four author-recorded lectures. Two conditions\n66\tare the historical path and its raw front-end: raw whisper-1 and AI_LectureNote. Two\n67\tare gpt-4o-transcribe conditions: raw chunked output and the same chunking with a single\n68\tminimal Korean prompt asking for English medical terms in English. The fifth condition,\n69\tgpt4o_ailn_post, applies the same AI_LectureNote post-processing to raw gpt-4o-transcribe\n70\toutput. This cross-input condition changes the upstream raw transcript while holding the\n71\tdownstream post-processing stage fixed.\n72\t   The pilot reveals a readability–faithfulness trade-off: post-processing improves English-script\n73\trendering, while observed semantic and polarity errors require separate evaluation of medical\n74\tmeaning.\n75\t   Accordingly, this report treats AI_LectureNote as a diagnostic case study in the trade-off\n76\tbetween readability-oriented post-ASR rewriting and medical-meaning faithfulness, rather than\n77\tas a benchmark of ASR systems. Detailed non-claims are handled in Limitations; the main\n78\tscope sentence is simple: this is a four-lecture, five-condition, single author-annotator pilot of\n79\tone historical workflow.\n80\t   Our contributions are:\n81\t   1. A five-condition retrospective protocol for evaluating a Korean–English medical study-\n82\t      transcript workflow, including a cross-input control that applies the same post-processing\n83\t      to a different raw ASR front-end.\n84\t   2. Two readability-oriented metrics — English-script rendering and chunk-level script con-\n85\t      sistency — reported separately from medical correctness.\n86\t   3. An operational labeling scheme for post-processed errors as introduced when raw ASR\n87\t      preserved the relevant information but post-processing lost or changed it, and propagated\n88\t      when post-processing carried forward an upstream ASR error.\n89\t\n90\t2. Related Work\n91\tCode-switched and medical ASR. Code-switching between a matrix language and embed-\n92\tded English is a known challenge for ASR, especially when the system must choose between\n93\tnative-script transliteration and English-script rendering (Sitaram et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2019;\n94\tPaik et al., 2025). Medical lecture speech adds technical terms, abbreviations, and morphology\n95\tthat are sparse in general-purpose training data. Recent medical ASR work similarly reports\n96\tthat domain terminology remains diﬀicult even when general transcription fluency is high (Ad-\n97\tedeji et al., 2024, 2025). Korean–English medical lectures combine these problems: the sentence\n98\tframe may be Korean, while many target concepts are conventionally learned and searched in\n99\tEnglish.\n100\t   LLM post-ASR correction. A common response to raw ASR errors is to place a language\n101\tmodel after the transcriber to clean, normalize, or correct the transcript. Recent work has\n102\texplored LLM-based correction pipelines for full-text speech recognition and specialized speech\n103\tsettings (Ma et al., 2023; Tang et al., 2025; Zheng et al., 2026). Such systems can improve\n104\treadability and reduce surface noise, but an unconstrained rewriting stage may also paraphrase,\n105\tcompress, substitute, or hallucinate content. This risk is easy to miss if evaluation stops at\n106\tWER or at a term-recall score. AI_LectureNote is a retrospective example of this pattern: a\n107\t\n108\t\n109\t                                                 2\n110\t\freadability-oriented LLM rewriting stage whose gains and costs can be measured separately.\n111\t    Domain-term rendering and normalization. Technical transcription often benefits from\n112\tcontextual biasing, hotword lists, or dynamic vocabulary methods that encourage systems to\n113\tretain or canonicalize domain terms (Sudo et al., 2024a, 2024b). These methods motivate a\n114\tmore constrained alternative to free-form rewriting. They also clarify why this paper uses\n115\t“English-script rendering” rather than “preservation” for the headline readability metric. A\n116\tcurated reference term is counted when it appears in English/Latin script in the output. This\n117\tis intentionally narrower than term correctness: a wrong English term can still be rendered in\n118\tEnglish script, and a hallucinated English term may not be penalized directly by recall.\n119\t    Safety-critical polarity and negation errors. Medical text is sensitive to directionality\n120\tand assertion status. Negation, uncertainty, and polarity cues have long been treated as first-\n121\tclass targets in clinical NLP because presence versus absence, increase versus decrease, and\n122\thypo- versus hyper- can change the meaning of a medical statement (Chapman et al., 2001;\n123\tUzuner et al., 2011; Peng et al., 2017). Lecture transcripts are not clinical records, but the same\n124\tlinguistic issue applies to study materials. A transcript that flips hypokalemia to hyperkalemia\n125\tor omits a directional cue is not merely less polished; it teaches a different claim. For this\n126\treason, polarity is annotated separately from general semantic drift.\n127\t\n128\t3. System Retrospective: AI_LectureNote\n129\tAI_LectureNote is a post-ASR, study-transcript generation workflow with the pipeline:\n130\taudio→raw ASR (whisper-1)→domain-aware LLM post-processing→study transcript\n131\t   After raw STT, AI_LectureNote operates on text: it chunks the raw transcript, applies a\n132\tcorrection pass for abnormal or disfluent wording, and then applies an “Englishing” pass that\n133\tconverts Korean-phonetic renderings of medical English terms into English/Latin script while\n134\tkeeping Korean sentences in Korean. The target output is therefore a readability-oriented study\n135\ttranscript rather than a verbatim conversational transcript. The workflow could optionally build\n136\ta knowledge graph from the resulting study transcript, but this stage was not enabled for the\n137\tpresent evaluation.\n138\t   This design motivates the faithfulness analysis. Because the post-processing stage is gen-\n139\terative rewriting rather than constrained glossary replacement, it can improve English-script\n140\trendering while introducing substitutions, omissions, compression, or polarity changes. We\n141\ttherefore evaluate AI_LectureNote as a readability-versus-faithfulness trade-off rather than as\n142\traw transcription accuracy.\n143\t   Two historical caveats matter for interpretation. This study does not evaluate the original\n144\tproduction corpus; instead, it re-runs the historical code with unchanged prompts and config-\n145\turation on four author-recorded lectures. The whisper-1 path was re-executed in 2026, so it\n146\tshould not be read as a 2023 snapshot. Because whisper-1 may have changed internally, we\n147\treport model names and execution dates but do not claim byte-for-byte historical reproduction.\n148\t\n149\t4. Pilot Materials and Evaluation Setup\n150\t4.1 Lectures and conditions\n151\tThe pilot uses four Korean–English medical lectures recorded specifically for this study by the\n152\tauthors, all delivered extemporaneously from loose AI-generated topic outlines without pre-\n153\twritten scripts or source texts. The recordings contain no patient data and are illustrative\n154\tteaching content whose medical accuracy is not guaranteed; all speaker voices are from the\n155\tauthor-speakers, who consented to research release.\n156\t\n157\t\n158\t\n159\t\n160\t                                                3\n161\t\f  Table 1. Lecture recordings used in the pilot.\n162\t             lecture                   topic                          duration   speaker\n163\t             diuretics_01              Diuretics                      13m 13s    lke\n164\t             acuteinflammation_02      Acute inflammation              13m 7s    lke\n165\t             anthrax_01                Anthrax (Bacillus anthracis)   12m 16s    cdh\n166\t             anticancerdrugs_02        Anticancer drugs                4m 30s    cdh\n167\t   Three lectures formed the initial pilot set; anticancerdrugs_02 was added later as a shorter\n168\tsame-speaker extension.\n169\t   From the same audio we produced five output conditions:\n170\t   1. raw whisper-1 — the historical pipeline’s raw ASR stage (whisper-1; Radford et al.,\n171\t      2023), re-executed in 2026 with per-lecture API dates recorded in the manifest.\n172\t   2. AI_LectureNote — whisper-1 output passed through the historical AI_LectureNote\n173\t      post-processing (code unchanged).\n174\t   3. raw gpt-4o-transcribe — the OpenAI gpt-4o-transcribe STT front-end (gpt-4o-\n175\t      transcribe; OpenAI, 2025) as accessed for this study, transcribed in 3-minute non-\n176\t      overlapping chunks.\n177\t   4. prompted gpt-4o-transcribe — the same chunking with a single Korean prompt (“의학\n178\t      강의 녹음입니다. 영어 의학 용어는 영어로 표기합니다.” — “This is a medical lecture recording.\n179\t      Write English medical terms in English.”), included only as a preliminary prompt-sensitivity\n180\t      check.\n181\t   5. gpt4o_ailn_post — raw gpt-4o-transcribe output from condition 3 passed through the\n182\t      same AI_LectureNote post-processing stage as condition 2. This condition serves as a\n183\t      cross-input diagnostic control rather than an optimized modern pipeline.\n184\t   For space, some figures abbreviate these condition names: raw gpt-4o-transcribe appears as\n185\t“gpt-4o raw”, and the two post-processed conditions (AI_LectureNote and gpt4o_ailn_post)\n186\tappear as “whisper→AILN” and “gpt4o→AILN post”.\n187\t\n188\t\n189\t\n190\t\n191\tFigure 1. Evaluation design. Four author-recorded lectures were processed into five outputs and scored\n192\tagainst author-created study-transcript references. The two post-processed conditions use the same\n193\thistorical AI_LectureNote rewriting stage.\n194\t\n195\t\n196\t\n197\t\n198\t                                                  4\n199\t\f4.2 Reference policy\n200\tThe references are author-created, lightly cleaned, content-preserving study transcripts, not\n201\tstrict verbatim conversational transcripts or independent gold-standard ASR references. They\n202\tpreserve medical content, English medical terms, polarity/direction cues, and medically imper-\n203\tfect speaker statements, while lightly regularizing non-content artifacts such as fillers, coughs,\n204\tabandoned fragments, and immediate stutter repetitions when this did not change the medical\n205\tclaim. Therefore, CER/WER should be interpreted relative to a study-transcript target rather\n206\tthan pure conversational-ASR accuracy. Rendering and semantic/polarity analyses are less sen-\n207\tsitive to fillers and spacing but still depend on this reference policy. Term canonicalization is\n208\thandled in annotation, not by editing the reference. The recordings and references are research\n209\tmaterials for evaluating transcription and post-ASR processing; they are not medical or educa-\n210\ttional guidance, and the medical accuracy of the spoken lecture content was not independently\n211\tverified.\n212\t\n213\t5. Metrics and Annotation\n214\t5.1 Metric definitions\n215\tNormalization and metric definitions were frozen before analysis: English text is lowercased,\n216\tpunctuation is mapped to spaces, and whitespace is collapsed; polarity morphemes (hypo/hyper,\n217\tacidosis/alkalosis) are never merged. The primary surface metric is CER (character error\n218\trate) computed on whitespace-stripped characters (removing the effect of Korean spacing).\n219\tWER (word error rate) is reported as a secondary metric on normalized tokens, but is less\n220\tinterpretable for paraphrased study transcripts.\n221\t   The headline readability metric is the English-script rendering rate: capped recall of\n222\tcurated reference domain-term occurrences rendered in English/Latin script. It measures script\n223\toccurrence, not whether the rendered term is medically correct in the correct sentence, and it\n224\tdoes not directly penalize hallucinated English-script terms except through missing reference\n225\tterms. The Korean phonetic count is the pooled count of curated reference domain terms\n226\trendered in Korean phonetic/transliterated script, summed over lectures. Per-lecture domain-\n227\tterm lists were initialized by automatically extracting Latin-script term candidates from the\n228\treference transcripts. The author curated the kept term set, canonical English forms, accepted\n229\tEnglish variants, and polarity tags. Korean phonetic variants were machine-assisted from ob-\n230\tserved ASR/STT outputs and used only for the descriptive phonetic-vs-omitted breakdown; they\n231\twere not exhaustively verified and may undercount Korean-phonetic renderings. The headline\n232\tEnglish-script rendering rate depends on canonical English forms and accepted English variants,\n233\tnot on the completeness of the korean_phonetic field. The chunk-level script-consistency\n234\tmeasure reports, for the chunked gpt-4o conditions, the per-3-minute-chunk proportion of ren-\n235\tdered curated domain-term tokens that appear in English/Latin rather than Korean phonetic\n236\tscript — that is, English / (English + phonetic) computed within the output, not a reference-\n237\tnormalized recall like the headline rate; chunks in which the output renders no curated domain\n238\tterm in either script carry no rate.\n239\t\n240\t5.2 Human annotation (single annotator, single pass)\n241\tHuman annotation was performed by a single author-annotator in one pass, without independent\n242\treplication or adjudication.\n243\t   • Semantic faithfulness: for the two post-processed conditions, every reference sentence\n244\t      was labeled with the taxonomy {Faithful, Minor rewrite, Omission, Addition, Substitution,\n245\t      Polarity error, Relation error, Unclear}. A drifted sentence received a primary drift label\n246\t      and, where applicable, one or more additional (compound) labels, so labels are not mutually\n247\t\n248\t\n249\t                                                5\n250\t\fTable 2. Cross-condition summary. CER, WER, and English-script rendering are lecture-\n251\tlevel macro means (each lecture weighted equally); Korean phonetic count, polarity failure,\n252\tand semantic drift are pooled counts over four lectures. Semantic drift was not annotated for\n253\tthe three raw-ASR conditions and is shown as “—”.\n254\t\n255\t                                               English-      Korean\n256\t                                                 script     phonetic      polarity\n257\t                                   WER       rendering        count         failure     semantic\n258\tcondition     CER (macro)        (macro)       (macro)      (pooled)      (pooled) drift (pooled)\n259\t\n260\traw                 0.3128        0.2966        0.3937           398             7            —\n261\twhisper-1\n262\tAI_LectureNote      0.3879        0.5843        0.7077            15           11             34\n263\traw gpt-4o-         0.3982        0.3067        0.2561           473           11             —\n264\ttranscribe\n265\tprompted            0.4342        0.3341        0.2198           429             9            —\n266\tgpt-4o-\n267\ttranscribe\n268\tgpt4o_ailn_post     0.4198        0.6078        0.6468            17           13             36\n269\t\n270\t      exclusive. We distinguish unique drifted rows (distinct drifted reference sentences; the\n271\t      drift_rows count) from taxonomy label incidences (per-category counts, which can\n272\t      exceed the number of drifted rows).\n273\t   • Critical polarity: every reference sentence carrying a polarity or direction cue is labeled\n274\t      per condition as correct / wrong / omitted.\n275\t   All quantitative results come from author-labeled worksheets; machine-generated draft labels\n276\twere used only as non-authoritative hints. Accordingly, rates are descriptive summaries rather\n277\tthan population estimates.\n278\t\n279\t6. Results\n280\tInterpretation is descriptive throughout; with four lectures we make no broad claims. Table 2\n281\tgives the cross-condition summary.\n282\t\n283\t6.1 Surface metrics do not capture the trade-off\n284\tMacro CER did not cleanly separate the five conditions, and the lowest CER was raw whisper-1\n285\trather than a post-processed condition. Post-processing improved surface distance mainly in\n286\tlectures with heavy transliteration, but worsened it when raw ASR was already close to the\n287\tstudy-transcript reference. This lecture-dependent pattern motivates reporting script rendering\n288\tand semantic faithfulness separately rather than relying on CER/WER alone. Because the\n289\tpost-processing stage rewrites the ASR output rather than retranscribing the audio, the sharp\n290\tincrease in WER after post-processing—0.30 to 0.58 for whisper-1 and 0.31 to 0.61 for gpt-4o—\n291\toffers a descriptive indication of substantial lexical rewriting introduced by post-processing,\n292\tconsistent with the observed surface-level drift.\n293\t\n294\t6.2 Post-processing raised English-script rendering in the pilot\n295\tTable 2 shows that post-processing improved macro English-script rendering on both whisper-\n296\t1 (0.39→0.71) and gpt-4o (0.26→0.65) paths, while reducing Korean phonetic occurrences from\n297\t398→15 and 473→17, respectively. The gain was largest where raw ASR transliterated most\n298\theavily (diuretics_01 rendering rate 0.05 → 0.77; acuteinflammation_02 rendering rate 0.16\n299\t→ 0.78), but was not guaranteed when raw output already had a high English-script rendering\n300\trate (anthrax_01 0.56 → 0.54; anticancerdrugs_02 0.81 → 0.75). Because the rendering rate\n301\t\n302\t\n303\t                                               6\n304\t\fmeasures script rather than medical correctness, these gains must be interpreted alongside the\n305\tdrift and polarity analyses in Section 6.3; a transcript can render many terms in English while\n306\tstill substituting medically wrong terms.\n307\t\n308\t\n309\t\n310\t\n311\tFigure 2. Readability gain versus observed faithfulness risk, N=4. Left: macro English-script rendering\n312\tby condition. Right: per-lecture semantic-drift rate for the two post-processed conditions.\n313\t\n314\t   Chunking and prompt sensitivity. Under the 3-minute gpt-4o chunking policy, per-chunk\n315\trendering varied sharply within lectures (acuteinflammation_02 0.94 then 0.07; diuretics_01\n316\t0.00–0.29; anticancerdrugs_02 0.38 then 0.96), consistent with script-selection instability. A\n317\tsingle minimal Korean prompt changed rendering inconsistently across lectures (diuretics_01\n318\t+0.12, anthrax_01 +0.13, acuteinflammation_02 −0.17, anticancerdrugs_02 −0.22), so we\n319\ttreat it only as preliminary prompt-sensitivity evidence.\n320\t\n321\t6.3 Observed faithfulness errors: semantic drift and polarity\n322\tSemantic drift. Semantic drift was annotated only for the two post-processed conditions, so\n323\tTable 3 should not be read as an aggregate raw-vs-post comparison. Table 3 reports unique\n324\tdrifted reference sentences, whereas Figure 3 reports drift-label incidences, which can exceed\n325\tunique-row counts because compound labels are allowed.\n326\t   Table 3. Semantic-drift summary for the two post-processed conditions. Faith-\n327\tful/minor/drift counts are row-level annotations; drift counts denote unique drifted reference\n328\tsentences.\n329\t\n330\t                               AI_LectureNote\n331\t                               faithful/              AI drift gpt4o_ailn_post          gpt4o_ailn_post\n332\tlecture                labeled minor/drift               rate faithful/minor/drift           drift rate\n333\tdiuretics_01               81 66 / 2 / 13              16.0% 56 / 6 / 19                         23.5%\n334\tacuteinflammation_02       71 57 / 4 / 10              14.1% 64 / 4 / 3                           4.2%\n335\tanthrax_01                 90 78 / 2 / 10              11.1% 76 / 3 / 11                         12.2%\n336\tanticancerdrugs_02         40 38 / 1 / 1                2.5% 37 / 0 / 3                           7.5%\n337\tpooled total              282 34                           — 36                                      —\n338\t   Semantic drift was observed in both post-processed conditions, with similar pooled counts\n339\tbut different lecture-level distributions. Table 3 therefore supports treating drift as workflow-\n340\tand input-sensitive rather than as a single aggregate rate. The redistribution of affected rows\n341\tmotivates the cross-input analysis in Section 6.4.\n342\t   Critical polarity. We report wrong and omitted separately but interpret a polarity failure\n343\tas the wrong + omitted set, pooled over 101 polarity-cue rows.\n344\t\n345\t\n346\t\n347\t\n348\t                                                  7\n349\t\fFigure 3. Semantic-drift taxonomy for the two post-processed conditions. Bars show drift-label inci-\n350\tdences by lecture and error type; labels are not mutually exclusive, so category counts can exceed unique\n351\tdrifted-row totals.\n352\t\n353\t  Table 4. Critical-polarity failures by condition. Counts are pooled over 101 polarity-\n354\tcue rows; failure is defined as wrong plus omitted.\n355\t                    condition               wrong        omitted   failure (= w + o)\n356\t                    raw whisper-1                7            0                   7\n357\t                    AI_LectureNote               8            3                  11\n358\t                    raw gpt-4o-transcribe       11            0                  11\n359\t                    prompted gpt-4o              9            0                   9\n360\t                    gpt4o_ailn_post              9            4                  13\n361\t\n362\t\n363\t\n364\t\n365\tFigure 4. Critical medical polarity, N=4. Panel (a) shows wrong and omitted polarity-cue rows by\n366\tcondition; panel (b) shows the whisper-1 → AI_LectureNote polarity transition for diuretics_01.\n367\t\n368\t   Polarity failures were rarer than general semantic drift but more clinically salient, and they\n369\tconcentrated in diuretics_01. Counting omissions together with wrong polarity changed\n370\tthe interpretation of post-processing performance: AI_LectureNote introduced omissions that\n371\twould be missed by a wrong-only count.\n372\t\n373\t6.4 Cross-input control: introduced versus propagated errors\n374\tTo examine why similar pooled drift counts produced different affected sentences, the cross-\n375\tinput control probes two candidate sources of post-processed errors. We label selected errors\n376\tas introduced when raw ASR preserved the relevant information but post-processing lost or\n377\tchanged it, and propagated when post-processing carried forward an upstream ASR error.\n378\t\n379\t                                                     8\n380\t\fRepresentative introduced errors included polarity or term substitutions such as “hypercal-\n381\tcemia” → “hypercalciuria,” whereas propagated errors included upstream substitutions such as\n382\t“lymphocyte” → “lipocyte.” Additional examples are listed in Appendix B.\n383\t   The two post-processed conditions showed different cross-input patterns in this pilot. For\n384\tdirectional polarity, the two conditions agreed on 95 of 101 rows, with a failure-set Jaccard\n385\tof 0.60 (9 shared of 15 unioned failures). Several rows that all raw front-ends transcribed cor-\n386\trectly flipped to the same wrong value after post-processing, consistent with a recurring post-\n387\tprocessing-associated polarity pattern. For general semantic drift, the overlap was much lower:\n388\tthe drift-set Jaccard was 0.23, with 13 shared drifted claims out of a union of 57. Aggregate\n389\tdrift was similar across the two post-processed conditions (34 vs. 36), but the affected sentences\n390\tshifted with the input ASR.\n391\t   This input sensitivity was clearest in acuteinflammation_02: applying the same post-\n392\tprocessing to gpt-4o output reduced drift from 10 to 3 and substitutions from 7 to 1, con-\n393\tsistent with fewer propagated whisper-path substitutions. At the same time, shared drift re-\n394\tmained across front-ends, especially in the diuretics_01 mechanism/electrolyte cluster and\n395\tanthrax_01 compression omissions. Thus, the control argues against treating the observed\n396\tgains and errors as merely whisper-1 artifacts: applying the same post-processing to raw gpt-4o\n397\talso raised English-script rendering (0.26 → 0.65), but did not eliminate observed faithfulness\n398\terrors. These patterns should be interpreted as workflow-specific.\n399\t\n400\t7. Discussion\n401\tFour points follow from the pilot.\n402\t   First, student-facing transcript utility is not the same as generic STT accuracy. The five con-\n403\tditions trade off differently across surface accuracy, term-script rendering, chunk consistency,\n404\tand medical-meaning preservation; CER/WER alone miss this trade-off. The original transliter-\n405\tation problem persisted in some lectures, including under the chunked gpt-4o condition, but not\n406\tuniformly. The clearest counterexample is anticancerdrugs_02, where raw whisper-1 already\n407\trendered 0.81 of curated terms in English script; this is also the shortest lecture (4m30s), so its\n408\thigh raw rendering may reflect length as well as content.\n409\t   Second, English-script rendering is a useful readability proxy for Korean–English medical\n410\tlectures, but it is not semantic faithfulness. A high rendering rate can coexist with wrong English\n411\tterms (Section 6.3), so script rendering and medical meaning must be measured separately.\n412\t   Third, post-ASR rewriting can improve readability while adding paraphrase, compression,\n413\tand faithfulness risks, especially when raw ASR is already close to the reference. The cross-\n414\tinput comparison suggests that some polarity failures were post-processing-associated, whereas\n415\tbroader semantic drift was more input-sensitive.\n416\t   Fourth, these findings should not be read as evidence that all domain-aware post-processing\n417\tintroduces semantic drift. AI_LectureNote is a readability-oriented LLM rewriting pipeline\n418\trather than a constrained term-normalization system; the diagnostic point is that script-\n419\trendering gains and semantic faithfulness should be evaluated separately.\n420\t\n421\t8. Limitations\n422\tThis retrospective pilot bounds every claim above; we make no benchmark, population-rate,\n423\teducational, or clinical claim.\n424\t  • Scale and confounding. Four lectures only. Speaker, topic, lecture length, and reference\n425\t     style remain confounded, even after adding a second cdh lecture.\n426\t  • Annotation provenance and evaluator overlap. References and labels were created\n427\t     via single-pass annotation by the system developers (single author-annotator) with no sec-\n428\t\n429\t                                                9\n430\t\f    ond pass, independent replication, adjudication, or inter-annotator agreement. Further-\n431\t    more, references are lightly cleaned study transcripts rather than gold-standard verbatim\n432\t    transcripts.\n433\t  • Polarity concentration. Polarity failures concentrate in diuretics_01, so polarity\n434\t    comparisons are illustrative rather than robust rate estimates.\n435\t  • Implementation choices. Condition 5 is a diagnostic control, not an optimized modern-\n436\t    STT post-processor; the gpt-4o conditions use 3-minute non-overlapping chunks and one\n437\t    minimal prompt, and the whisper-1 condition is a 2026 rerun rather than a 2023 snapshot.\n438\t  • Metric scope. English-script rendering is recall-like and script-only; it does not measure\n439\t    term correctness or hallucinated terms except through missed reference terms.\n440\t  • Korean-phonetic diagnostic counts. The Korean-phonetic counts are diagnostic lower-\n441\t    bound counts based on a machine-assisted list of observed phonetic variants; the phonetic\n442\t    variant lists were not exhaustively verified.\n443\t\n444\t9. Conclusion\n445\tAcross four author-recorded lectures, AI_LectureNote-style post-processing improved English-\n446\tscript rendering on both input paths, but these readability gains coexisted with semantic drift\n447\tand polarity failures. The cross-input control suggested that polarity failures were more stable\n448\tacross raw front-ends than general semantic drift, whose affected sentences shifted with the\n449\tinput ASR. The central methodological takeaway is that surface distance, term-script render-\n450\ting, chunk-level consistency, and medical-meaning preservation should be evaluated separately.\n451\tFuture work should test more constrained alternatives, such as span-level glossary replacement,\n452\tverifier-backed correction, or constrained rewriting.\n453\t\n454\t10. Reproducibility / Data and Code Availability\n455\tFrom the evaluation_paper/ directory, all tables and figures regenerate with python\n456\tanalysis/run_all.py. Source files are organized as (paths relative to evaluation_paper/):\n457\t   • References\n458\t      data/<lecture>/reference.txt\n459\t   • Semantic labels\n460\t      annotations/<lecture>/semantic_review.csv\n461\t   • Condition-5 semantic labels\n462\t      annotations/<lecture>/semantic_review_gpt4o_ailn_post.csv\n463\t   • Polarity labels\n464\t      annotations/<lecture>/polarity_review.csv\n465\t   • Domain terms\n466\t      annotations/<lecture>/domain_terms.csv\n467\t   • Condition manifest\n468\t      manifest/condition_manifest.csv\n469\t   The condition manifest records model names, API dates, prompt text, and the condition-5\n470\tpipeline description.\n471\t   Code, speaker-coded evaluation transcripts, references, annotation files, and generated tables/\n472\tfigures are released in the public repository: https://github.com/boyskier/ailecturenote-\n473\tretrospective-pilot. Where audio is included, it is released with explicit author-speaker consent\n474\tfor research reproducibility; because the audio contains identifiable voices, it should not be\n475\ttreated as anonymized.\n476\t\n477\t\n478\t\n479\t\n480\t                                               10\n481\t\fAcknowledgements\n482\tWe thank Professor Hogun Park for supervising the 2024 CO-Deep Learning student project\n483\tthat laid the foundation for this work.\n484\t\n485\tAppendix A. Supplementary figures\n486\tThe four main figures appear inline (Figure 1, Section 4.1; Figure 2, Section 6.2; Figure 3 and\n487\tFigure 4, Section 6.3). The following supplementary figures provide per-lecture detail and are\n488\treproduced by python analysis/run_all.py:\n489\t   • Figure S1 (figures/fig2_cer_wer.png) — per-lecture CER (primary) and WER\n490\t     (secondary) for all five conditions, showing the anthrax_01 and anticancerdrugs_02\n491\t     divergence where raw whisper-1 is clean but post-processing raises CER (Section 6.1).\n492\t   • Figure S2 (figures/fig1_english_script_rate.png) — English-script rendering rate\n493\t     by condition and lecture, the per-lecture detail behind the headline trade-off in Figure 2\n494\t     (Section 6.2).\n495\t   • Figures S3a–d (figures/fig3_chunk_<lecture>.png) — per-3-minute-chunk English\n496\t     vs. Korean-phonetic counts for raw and prompted gpt-4o, one panel per lecture\n497\t     (acuteinflammation_02, anthrax_01, anticancerdrugs_02, diuretics_01), illustrating\n498\t     the chunk-level script instability (Section 6.2).\n499\t\n500\tAppendix B. Illustrative errors\n501\tAppendix B lists illustrative author-reviewed errors.         The examples are drawn from\n502\ttable7_semantic_drift_examples.csv. Examples include propagated substitutions such\n503\tas lymphocyte → “lipocyte” and tissue edema → “tissue adenoma”; introduced or post-\n504\tprocessing-associated polarity/substitution errors such as hypercalcemia → “hypercalciuria”\n505\tand hypokalemia-prevention → “hyperkalemia-prevention”; and additions such as an unmen-\n506\ttioned “ibuprofen” in the ototoxicity discussion. Condition 5 also produced a concept error in\n507\tanticancerdrugs_02, conflating antimetabolites with alkylating agents.\n508\t   For balance, post-processing also corrected some upstream errors in anthrax_01, including\n509\trestoring whisper-1’s “Annihilation” to “Inhalation”, preserving the 90–95% / 20% mortality\n510\tfigures, and restoring the PA/EF/LF abbreviations in English. Thus, the examples illustrate\n511\tmixed effects of readability-oriented rewriting rather than a one-directional degradation.\n512\t\n513\t\n514\t\n515\tReferences\n516\t  • Adedeji, A., Joshi, S., & Doohan, B. (2024). The Sound of Healthcare: Improving Medical\n517\t    Transcription ASR Accuracy with Large Language Models. arXiv:2402.07658.\n518\t  • Adedeji, A., Sanni, M., Ayodele, E., Joshi, S., & Olatunji, T. (2025). The Multi-\n519\t    cultural Medical Assistant: Can LLMs Improve Medical ASR Errors Across Borders?\n520\t    arXiv:2501.15310.\n521\t  • Chapman, W. W., Bridewell, W., Hanbury, P., Cooper, G. F., & Buchanan, B. G. (2001).\n522\t    A simple algorithm for identifying negated findings and diseases in discharge summaries.\n523\t    Journal of Biomedical Informatics, 34(5), 301–310. doi:10.1006/jbin.2001.1029.\n524\t  • Ma, R., Qian, M., Manakul, P., Gales, M., & Knill, K. (2023). Can Generative Large\n525\t    Language Models Perform ASR Error Correction? arXiv:2307.04172.\n526\t  • OpenAI. (2025). Speech to text. OpenAI API documentation. Accessed 2026-06-27.\n527\t    https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/speech-to-text\n528\t  • Paik, G., Kim, Y., Lee, S., Ahn, S., & Kim, C. (2025). HiKE: Hierarchical Evaluation\n529\t\n530\t\n531\t                                              11\n532\t\f  Framework for Korean–English Code-Switching Speech Recognition. arXiv:2509.24613.\n533\t• Peng, Y., Wang, X., Lu, L., Bagheri, M., Summers, R. M., & Lu, Z. (2017). Neg-\n534\t  Bio: a high-performance tool for negation and uncertainty detection in radiology reports.\n535\t  arXiv:1712.05898.\n536\t• Radford, A., Kim, J. W., Xu, T., Brockman, G., McLeavey, C., & Sutskever, I.\n537\t  (2023). Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision (Whisper). Proceed-\n538\t  ings of the 40th International Conference on Machine Learning, PMLR 202:28492–28518.\n539\t  arXiv:2212.04356.\n540\t• Sitaram, S., Chandu, K. R., Rallabandi, S. K., & Black, A. W. (2019). A survey of\n541\t  code-switched speech and language processing. arXiv:1904.00784.\n542\t• Sudo, Y., Shakeel, M., Fukumoto, Y., Peng, Y., & Watanabe, S. (2024a). Contextualized\n543\t  Automatic Speech Recognition with Attention-Based Bias Phrase Boosted Beam Search.\n544\t  arXiv:2401.10449.\n545\t• Sudo, Y., Fukumoto, Y., Shakeel, M., Peng, Y., & Watanabe, S. (2024b). Contextualized\n546\t  Automatic Speech Recognition with Dynamic Vocabulary. arXiv:2405.13344.\n547\t• Tang, Z., Wang, D., Zhou, Z., Liu, Y., Huang, S., & Shang, S. (2025). Chain of Correction\n548\t  for Full-text Speech Recognition with Large Language Models. arXiv:2504.01519.\n549\t• Uzuner, Ö., South, B. R., Shen, S., & DuVall, S. L. (2011). 2010 i2b2/VA challenge\n550\t  on concepts, assertions, and relations in clinical text. Journal of the American Medical\n551\t  Informatics Association, 18(5), 552–556. doi:10.1136/amiajnl-2011-000203.\n552\t• Wang, J., Kim, J., Kim, S., & Lee, Y. (2019). Exploring Lexicon-Free Modeling\n553\t  Units for End-to-End Korean and Korean–English Code-Switching Speech Recognition.\n554\t  arXiv:1910.11590.\n555\t• Zheng, X., Dong, S., Phukon, B., Hasegawa-Johnson, M., & Yoo, C. D. (2026). Towards\n556\t  Robust Dysarthric Speech Recognition: LLM-Agent Post-ASR Correction Beyond WER.\n557\t  arXiv:2601.21347.\n558\t\n559\t\n560\t\n561\t\n562\t                                          12\n563\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "acf04907-0419-455e-8520-9e153f617dd5", "uuid": "e5a50ede-56dc-4874-9c5f-a74215f4f2c1", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T10:40:40.674Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/2607.17237v1.txt", "content": "                                          AI_LectureNote: A Retrospective Pilot Study of a Post-ASR\n                                          Workflow for English-Script Rendering and Semantic Drift in\n                                                       Korean–English Medical Lectures\n                                                               Kyeongeon Lee, Donghoon Chang, Seungryeol Baek,\n                                                                         Taehong Kim, Wonjun Yang\n                                                                     Sungkyunkwan University, Republic of Korea\n                                                          boy.skier@g.skku.edu dhchang5765@gmail.com bsr20030507@g.skku.edu\n                                                                        jinanara@skku.edu judereal15@gmail.com\n\n\n\n                                                                                        Abstract\n                                                  AI_LectureNote is a historical, readability-oriented post-ASR workflow for Korean–\n                                              English medical lectures. It rewrites speech-to-text output into study transcripts while\n                                              restoring Latin-script medical terms rather than Korean phonetic transliterations. We ret-\n                                              rospectively evaluate the workflow on four author-recorded lectures across five conditions.\n                                              In this pilot, post-processing raised the macro English-script rendering rate from 0.39 to\narXiv:2607.17237v1 [cs.CL] 19 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                              0.71 on the whisper-1 path and from 0.26 to 0.65 when applied to 3-minute chunked gpt-4o-\n                                              transcribe output. However, English-script rendering did not imply semantic faithfulness:\n                                              the two post-processed conditions showed semantic drift in 34 and 36 of 282 reference sen-\n                                              tences and polarity failures in 11 and 13 of 101 polarity-cue rows. A descriptive cross-input\n                                              comparison suggested different candidate failure patterns: polarity-failure sets overlapped\n                                              more strongly across front-ends (Jaccard 0.60; 9 shared of 15 unioned failures) than general\n                                              semantic-drift sets (Jaccard 0.23; 13 shared of 57 unioned drifts). This single-annotator pilot\n                                              documents concrete failure modes rather than population rates and supports evaluating sur-\n                                              face accuracy, term-script rendering, chunk-level script consistency, and medical-meaning\n                                              preservation separately.\n\n\n\n                                         1. Introduction\n                                         Students using recorded Korean–English medical lectures often need something different from\n                                         a verbatim acoustic transcript. A useful study transcript should keep the lecturer’s medical\n                                         claims readable, render English medical terminology in English script, and retain clinically or\n                                         biologically important directionality. Generic ASR metrics do not directly measure this target.\n                                         In Korean–English medical lectures, the gap is especially visible when ASR renders embedded\n                                         English terms as Korean phonetic strings (for example, “carbonic anhydrase inhibitor” may\n                                         be rendered as “카르보닉 아나이드레이즈 이니비터”), producing fluent-looking but hard-to-study\n                                         transcripts.\n                                            AI_LectureNote was built for that practical problem. It was a student-built prototype\n                                         that used the OpenAI whisper-1 API as its raw ASR front-end and added domain-aware\n                                         post-processing to restore medical terms and regularize wording into a study transcript. The\n                                         system originated as an internal study aid. Here, we re-run that historical post-processing code\n                                         unchanged and evaluate it retrospectively.\n                                            The central distinction is between readability and faithfulness. English-script rendering\n                                         makes a transcript easier to scan, search, and align with textbooks, but it can hide different\n                                         errors. A rewritten transcript may replace a Korean phonetic string with an English medical\n                                         word that looks plausible while being the wrong word. It may compress an explanation and\n                                         drop the causal relation, or it may flip a polarity cue such as hypo- versus hyper-. These are\n                                         not only formatting errors; they alter what a student would study.\n\n\n                                                                                            1\n\f   The motivating question is therefore not whether AI_LectureNote is a better ASR system\nthan a modern commercial transcriber. The question is narrower: when readability-oriented\npost-ASR rewriting improves English-script rendering, what happens to medical-meaning faith-\nfulness? This question remains relevant even with newer raw STT front-ends such as gpt-4o-\ntranscribe, because fluent raw output and readable post-processed output can fail in different\nways.\n   We compare five conditions over the same four author-recorded lectures. Two conditions\nare the historical path and its raw front-end: raw whisper-1 and AI_LectureNote. Two\nare gpt-4o-transcribe conditions: raw chunked output and the same chunking with a single\nminimal Korean prompt asking for English medical terms in English. The fifth condition,\ngpt4o_ailn_post, applies the same AI_LectureNote post-processing to raw gpt-4o-transcribe\noutput. This cross-input condition changes the upstream raw transcript while holding the\ndownstream post-processing stage fixed.\n   The pilot reveals a readability–faithfulness trade-off: post-processing improves English-script\nrendering, while observed semantic and polarity errors require separate evaluation of medical\nmeaning.\n   Accordingly, this report treats AI_LectureNote as a diagnostic case study in the trade-off\nbetween readability-oriented post-ASR rewriting and medical-meaning faithfulness, rather than\nas a benchmark of ASR systems. Detailed non-claims are handled in Limitations; the main\nscope sentence is simple: this is a four-lecture, five-condition, single author-annotator pilot of\none historical workflow.\n   Our contributions are:\n   1. A five-condition retrospective protocol for evaluating a Korean–English medical study-\n      transcript workflow, including a cross-input control that applies the same post-processing\n      to a different raw ASR front-end.\n   2. Two readability-oriented metrics — English-script rendering and chunk-level script con-\n      sistency — reported separately from medical correctness.\n   3. An operational labeling scheme for post-processed errors as introduced when raw ASR\n      preserved the relevant information but post-processing lost or changed it, and propagated\n      when post-processing carried forward an upstream ASR error.\n\n2. Related Work\nCode-switched and medical ASR. Code-switching between a matrix language and embed-\nded English is a known challenge for ASR, especially when the system must choose between\nnative-script transliteration and English-script rendering (Sitaram et al., 2019; Wang et al., 2019;\nPaik et al., 2025). Medical lecture speech adds technical terms, abbreviations, and morphology\nthat are sparse in general-purpose training data. Recent medical ASR work similarly reports\nthat domain terminology remains diﬀicult even when general transcription fluency is high (Ad-\nedeji et al., 2024, 2025). Korean–English medical lectures combine these problems: the sentence\nframe may be Korean, while many target concepts are conventionally learned and searched in\nEnglish.\n   LLM post-ASR correction. A common response to raw ASR errors is to place a language\nmodel after the transcriber to clean, normalize, or correct the transcript. Recent work has\nexplored LLM-based correction pipelines for full-text speech recognition and specialized speech\nsettings (Ma et al., 2023; Tang et al., 2025; Zheng et al., 2026). Such systems can improve\nreadability and reduce surface noise, but an unconstrained rewriting stage may also paraphrase,\ncompress, substitute, or hallucinate content. This risk is easy to miss if evaluation stops at\nWER or at a term-recall score. AI_LectureNote is a retrospective example of this pattern: a\n\n\n                                                 2\n\freadability-oriented LLM rewriting stage whose gains and costs can be measured separately.\n    Domain-term rendering and normalization. Technical transcription often benefits from\ncontextual biasing, hotword lists, or dynamic vocabulary methods that encourage systems to\nretain or canonicalize domain terms (Sudo et al., 2024a, 2024b). These methods motivate a\nmore constrained alternative to free-form rewriting. They also clarify why this paper uses\n“English-script rendering” rather than “preservation” for the headline readability metric. A\ncurated reference term is counted when it appears in English/Latin script in the output. This\nis intentionally narrower than term correctness: a wrong English term can still be rendered in\nEnglish script, and a hallucinated English term may not be penalized directly by recall.\n    Safety-critical polarity and negation errors. Medical text is sensitive to directionality\nand assertion status. Negation, uncertainty, and polarity cues have long been treated as first-\nclass targets in clinical NLP because presence versus absence, increase versus decrease, and\nhypo- versus hyper- can change the meaning of a medical statement (Chapman et al., 2001;\nUzuner et al., 2011; Peng et al., 2017). Lecture transcripts are not clinical records, but the same\nlinguistic issue applies to study materials. A transcript that flips hypokalemia to hyperkalemia\nor omits a directional cue is not merely less polished; it teaches a different claim. For this\nreason, polarity is annotated separately from general semantic drift.\n\n3. System Retrospective: AI_LectureNote\nAI_LectureNote is a post-ASR, study-transcript generation workflow with the pipeline:\naudio→raw ASR (whisper-1)→domain-aware LLM post-processing→study transcript\n   After raw STT, AI_LectureNote operates on text: it chunks the raw transcript, applies a\ncorrection pass for abnormal or disfluent wording, and then applies an “Englishing” pass that\nconverts Korean-phonetic renderings of medical English terms into English/Latin script while\nkeeping Korean sentences in Korean. The target output is therefore a readability-oriented study\ntranscript rather than a verbatim conversational transcript. The workflow could optionally build\na knowledge graph from the resulting study transcript, but this stage was not enabled for the\npresent evaluation.\n   This design motivates the faithfulness analysis. Because the post-processing stage is gen-\nerative rewriting rather than constrained glossary replacement, it can improve English-script\nrendering while introducing substitutions, omissions, compression, or polarity changes. We\ntherefore evaluate AI_LectureNote as a readability-versus-faithfulness trade-off rather than as\nraw transcription accuracy.\n   Two historical caveats matter for interpretation. This study does not evaluate the original\nproduction corpus; instead, it re-runs the historical code with unchanged prompts and config-\nuration on four author-recorded lectures. The whisper-1 path was re-executed in 2026, so it\nshould not be read as a 2023 snapshot. Because whisper-1 may have changed internally, we\nreport model names and execution dates but do not claim byte-for-byte historical reproduction.\n\n4. Pilot Materials and Evaluation Setup\n4.1 Lectures and conditions\nThe pilot uses four Korean–English medical lectures recorded specifically for this study by the\nauthors, all delivered extemporaneously from loose AI-generated topic outlines without pre-\nwritten scripts or source texts. The recordings contain no patient data and are illustrative\nteaching content whose medical accuracy is not guaranteed; all speaker voices are from the\nauthor-speakers, who consented to research release.\n\n\n\n\n                                                3\n\f  Table 1. Lecture recordings used in the pilot.\n             lecture                   topic                          duration   speaker\n             diuretics_01              Diuretics                      13m 13s    lke\n             acuteinflammation_02      Acute inflammation              13m 7s    lke\n             anthrax_01                Anthrax (Bacillus anthracis)   12m 16s    cdh\n             anticancerdrugs_02        Anticancer drugs                4m 30s    cdh\n   Three lectures formed the initial pilot set; anticancerdrugs_02 was added later as a shorter\nsame-speaker extension.\n   From the same audio we produced five output conditions:\n   1. raw whisper-1 — the historical pipeline’s raw ASR stage (whisper-1; Radford et al.,\n      2023), re-executed in 2026 with per-lecture API dates recorded in the manifest.\n   2. AI_LectureNote — whisper-1 output passed through the historical AI_LectureNote\n      post-processing (code unchanged).\n   3. raw gpt-4o-transcribe — the OpenAI gpt-4o-transcribe STT front-end (gpt-4o-\n      transcribe; OpenAI, 2025) as accessed for this study, transcribed in 3-minute non-\n      overlapping chunks.\n   4. prompted gpt-4o-transcribe — the same chunking with a single Korean prompt (“의학\n      강의 녹음입니다. 영어 의학 용어는 영어로 표기합니다.” — “This is a medical lecture recording.\n      Write English medical terms in English.”), included only as a preliminary prompt-sensitivity\n      check.\n   5. gpt4o_ailn_post — raw gpt-4o-transcribe output from condition 3 passed through the\n      same AI_LectureNote post-processing stage as condition 2. This condition serves as a\n      cross-input diagnostic control rather than an optimized modern pipeline.\n   For space, some figures abbreviate these condition names: raw gpt-4o-transcribe appears as\n“gpt-4o raw”, and the two post-processed conditions (AI_LectureNote and gpt4o_ailn_post)\nappear as “whisper→AILN” and “gpt4o→AILN post”.\n\n\n\n\nFigure 1. Evaluation design. Four author-recorded lectures were processed into five outputs and scored\nagainst author-created study-transcript references. The two post-processed conditions use the same\nhistorical AI_LectureNote rewriting stage.\n\n\n\n\n                                                  4\n\f4.2 Reference policy\nThe references are author-created, lightly cleaned, content-preserving study transcripts, not\nstrict verbatim conversational transcripts or independent gold-standard ASR references. They\npreserve medical content, English medical terms, polarity/direction cues, and medically imper-\nfect speaker statements, while lightly regularizing non-content artifacts such as fillers, coughs,\nabandoned fragments, and immediate stutter repetitions when this did not change the medical\nclaim. Therefore, CER/WER should be interpreted relative to a study-transcript target rather\nthan pure conversational-ASR accuracy. Rendering and semantic/polarity analyses are less sen-\nsitive to fillers and spacing but still depend on this reference policy. Term canonicalization is\nhandled in annotation, not by editing the reference. The recordings and references are research\nmaterials for evaluating transcription and post-ASR processing; they are not medical or educa-\ntional guidance, and the medical accuracy of the spoken lecture content was not independently\nverified.\n\n5. Metrics and Annotation\n5.1 Metric definitions\nNormalization and metric definitions were frozen before analysis: English text is lowercased,\npunctuation is mapped to spaces, and whitespace is collapsed; polarity morphemes (hypo/hyper,\nacidosis/alkalosis) are never merged. The primary surface metric is CER (character error\nrate) computed on whitespace-stripped characters (removing the effect of Korean spacing).\nWER (word error rate) is reported as a secondary metric on normalized tokens, but is less\ninterpretable for paraphrased study transcripts.\n   The headline readability metric is the English-script rendering rate: capped recall of\ncurated reference domain-term occurrences rendered in English/Latin script. It measures script\noccurrence, not whether the rendered term is medically correct in the correct sentence, and it\ndoes not directly penalize hallucinated English-script terms except through missing reference\nterms. The Korean phonetic count is the pooled count of curated reference domain terms\nrendered in Korean phonetic/transliterated script, summed over lectures. Per-lecture domain-\nterm lists were initialized by automatically extracting Latin-script term candidates from the\nreference transcripts. The author curated the kept term set, canonical English forms, accepted\nEnglish variants, and polarity tags. Korean phonetic variants were machine-assisted from ob-\nserved ASR/STT outputs and used only for the descriptive phonetic-vs-omitted breakdown; they\nwere not exhaustively verified and may undercount Korean-phonetic renderings. The headline\nEnglish-script rendering rate depends on canonical English forms and accepted English variants,\nnot on the completeness of the korean_phonetic field. The chunk-level script-consistency\nmeasure reports, for the chunked gpt-4o conditions, the per-3-minute-chunk proportion of ren-\ndered curated domain-term tokens that appear in English/Latin rather than Korean phonetic\nscript — that is, English / (English + phonetic) computed within the output, not a reference-\nnormalized recall like the headline rate; chunks in which the output renders no curated domain\nterm in either script carry no rate.\n\n5.2 Human annotation (single annotator, single pass)\nHuman annotation was performed by a single author-annotator in one pass, without independent\nreplication or adjudication.\n   • Semantic faithfulness: for the two post-processed conditions, every reference sentence\n      was labeled with the taxonomy {Faithful, Minor rewrite, Omission, Addition, Substitution,\n      Polarity error, Relation error, Unclear}. A drifted sentence received a primary drift label\n      and, where applicable, one or more additional (compound) labels, so labels are not mutually\n\n\n                                                5\n\fTable 2. Cross-condition summary. CER, WER, and English-script rendering are lecture-\nlevel macro means (each lecture weighted equally); Korean phonetic count, polarity failure,\nand semantic drift are pooled counts over four lectures. Semantic drift was not annotated for\nthe three raw-ASR conditions and is shown as “—”.\n\n                                               English-      Korean\n                                                 script     phonetic      polarity\n                                   WER       rendering        count         failure     semantic\ncondition     CER (macro)        (macro)       (macro)      (pooled)      (pooled) drift (pooled)\n\nraw                 0.3128        0.2966        0.3937           398             7            —\nwhisper-1\nAI_LectureNote      0.3879        0.5843        0.7077            15           11             34\nraw gpt-4o-         0.3982        0.3067        0.2561           473           11             —\ntranscribe\nprompted            0.4342        0.3341        0.2198           429             9            —\ngpt-4o-\ntranscribe\ngpt4o_ailn_post     0.4198        0.6078        0.6468            17           13             36\n\n      exclusive. We distinguish unique drifted rows (distinct drifted reference sentences; the\n      drift_rows count) from taxonomy label incidences (per-category counts, which can\n      exceed the number of drifted rows).\n   • Critical polarity: every reference sentence carrying a polarity or direction cue is labeled\n      per condition as correct / wrong / omitted.\n   All quantitative results come from author-labeled worksheets; machine-generated draft labels\nwere used only as non-authoritative hints. Accordingly, rates are descriptive summaries rather\nthan population estimates.\n\n6. Results\nInterpretation is descriptive throughout; with four lectures we make no broad claims. Table 2\ngives the cross-condition summary.\n\n6.1 Surface metrics do not capture the trade-off\nMacro CER did not cleanly separate the five conditions, and the lowest CER was raw whisper-1\nrather than a post-processed condition. Post-processing improved surface distance mainly in\nlectures with heavy transliteration, but worsened it when raw ASR was already close to the\nstudy-transcript reference. This lecture-dependent pattern motivates reporting script rendering\nand semantic faithfulness separately rather than relying on CER/WER alone. Because the\npost-processing stage rewrites the ASR output rather than retranscribing the audio, the sharp\nincrease in WER after post-processing—0.30 to 0.58 for whisper-1 and 0.31 to 0.61 for gpt-4o—\noffers a descriptive indication of substantial lexical rewriting introduced by post-processing,\nconsistent with the observed surface-level drift.\n\n6.2 Post-processing raised English-script rendering in the pilot\nTable 2 shows that post-processing improved macro English-script rendering on both whisper-\n1 (0.39→0.71) and gpt-4o (0.26→0.65) paths, while reducing Korean phonetic occurrences from\n398→15 and 473→17, respectively. The gain was largest where raw ASR transliterated most\nheavily (diuretics_01 rendering rate 0.05 → 0.77; acuteinflammation_02 rendering rate 0.16\n→ 0.78), but was not guaranteed when raw output already had a high English-script rendering\nrate (anthrax_01 0.56 → 0.54; anticancerdrugs_02 0.81 → 0.75). Because the rendering rate\n\n\n                                               6\n\fmeasures script rather than medical correctness, these gains must be interpreted alongside the\ndrift and polarity analyses in Section 6.3; a transcript can render many terms in English while\nstill substituting medically wrong terms.\n\n\n\n\nFigure 2. Readability gain versus observed faithfulness risk, N=4. Left: macro English-script rendering\nby condition. Right: per-lecture semantic-drift rate for the two post-processed conditions.\n\n   Chunking and prompt sensitivity. Under the 3-minute gpt-4o chunking policy, per-chunk\nrendering varied sharply within lectures (acuteinflammation_02 0.94 then 0.07; diuretics_01\n0.00–0.29; anticancerdrugs_02 0.38 then 0.96), consistent with script-selection instability. A\nsingle minimal Korean prompt changed rendering inconsistently across lectures (diuretics_01\n+0.12, anthrax_01 +0.13, acuteinflammation_02 −0.17, anticancerdrugs_02 −0.22), so we\ntreat it only as preliminary prompt-sensitivity evidence.\n\n6.3 Observed faithfulness errors: semantic drift and polarity\nSemantic drift. Semantic drift was annotated only for the two post-processed conditions, so\nTable 3 should not be read as an aggregate raw-vs-post comparison. Table 3 reports unique\ndrifted reference sentences, whereas Figure 3 reports drift-label incidences, which can exceed\nunique-row counts because compound labels are allowed.\n   Table 3. Semantic-drift summary for the two post-processed conditions. Faith-\nful/minor/drift counts are row-level annotations; drift counts denote unique drifted reference\nsentences.\n\n                               AI_LectureNote\n                               faithful/              AI drift gpt4o_ailn_post          gpt4o_ailn_post\nlecture                labeled minor/drift               rate faithful/minor/drift           drift rate\ndiuretics_01               81 66 / 2 / 13              16.0% 56 / 6 / 19                         23.5%\nacuteinflammation_02       71 57 / 4 / 10              14.1% 64 / 4 / 3                           4.2%\nanthrax_01                 90 78 / 2 / 10              11.1% 76 / 3 / 11                         12.2%\nanticancerdrugs_02         40 38 / 1 / 1                2.5% 37 / 0 / 3                           7.5%\npooled total              282 34                           — 36                                      —\n   Semantic drift was observed in both post-processed conditions, with similar pooled counts\nbut different lecture-level distributions. Table 3 therefore supports treating drift as workflow-\nand input-sensitive rather than as a single aggregate rate. The redistribution of affected rows\nmotivates the cross-input analysis in Section 6.4.\n   Critical polarity. We report wrong and omitted separately but interpret a polarity failure\nas the wrong + omitted set, pooled over 101 polarity-cue rows.\n\n\n\n\n                                                  7\n\fFigure 3. Semantic-drift taxonomy for the two post-processed conditions. Bars show drift-label inci-\ndences by lecture and error type; labels are not mutually exclusive, so category counts can exceed unique\ndrifted-row totals.\n\n  Table 4. Critical-polarity failures by condition. Counts are pooled over 101 polarity-\ncue rows; failure is defined as wrong plus omitted.\n                    condition               wrong        omitted   failure (= w + o)\n                    raw whisper-1                7            0                   7\n                    AI_LectureNote               8            3                  11\n                    raw gpt-4o-transcribe       11            0                  11\n                    prompted gpt-4o              9            0                   9\n                    gpt4o_ailn_post              9            4                  13\n\n\n\n\nFigure 4. Critical medical polarity, N=4. Panel (a) shows wrong and omitted polarity-cue rows by\ncondition; panel (b) shows the whisper-1 → AI_LectureNote polarity transition for diuretics_01.\n\n   Polarity failures were rarer than general semantic drift but more clinically salient, and they\nconcentrated in diuretics_01. Counting omissions together with wrong polarity changed\nthe interpretation of post-processing performance: AI_LectureNote introduced omissions that\nwould be missed by a wrong-only count.\n\n6.4 Cross-input control: introduced versus propagated errors\nTo examine why similar pooled drift counts produced different affected sentences, the cross-\ninput control probes two candidate sources of post-processed errors. We label selected errors\nas introduced when raw ASR preserved the relevant information but post-processing lost or\nchanged it, and propagated when post-processing carried forward an upstream ASR error.\n\n                                                     8\n\fRepresentative introduced errors included polarity or term substitutions such as “hypercal-\ncemia” → “hypercalciuria,” whereas propagated errors included upstream substitutions such as\n“lymphocyte” → “lipocyte.” Additional examples are listed in Appendix B.\n   The two post-processed conditions showed different cross-input patterns in this pilot. For\ndirectional polarity, the two conditions agreed on 95 of 101 rows, with a failure-set Jaccard\nof 0.60 (9 shared of 15 unioned failures). Several rows that all raw front-ends transcribed cor-\nrectly flipped to the same wrong value after post-processing, consistent with a recurring post-\nprocessing-associated polarity pattern. For general semantic drift, the overlap was much lower:\nthe drift-set Jaccard was 0.23, with 13 shared drifted claims out of a union of 57. Aggregate\ndrift was similar across the two post-processed conditions (34 vs. 36), but the affected sentences\nshifted with the input ASR.\n   This input sensitivity was clearest in acuteinflammation_02: applying the same post-\nprocessing to gpt-4o output reduced drift from 10 to 3 and substitutions from 7 to 1, con-\nsistent with fewer propagated whisper-path substitutions. At the same time, shared drift re-\nmained across front-ends, especially in the diuretics_01 mechanism/electrolyte cluster and\nanthrax_01 compression omissions. Thus, the control argues against treating the observed\ngains and errors as merely whisper-1 artifacts: applying the same post-processing to raw gpt-4o\nalso raised English-script rendering (0.26 → 0.65), but did not eliminate observed faithfulness\nerrors. These patterns should be interpreted as workflow-specific.\n\n7. Discussion\nFour points follow from the pilot.\n   First, student-facing transcript utility is not the same as generic STT accuracy. The five con-\nditions trade off differently across surface accuracy, term-script rendering, chunk consistency,\nand medical-meaning preservation; CER/WER alone miss this trade-off. The original transliter-\nation problem persisted in some lectures, including under the chunked gpt-4o condition, but not\nuniformly. The clearest counterexample is anticancerdrugs_02, where raw whisper-1 already\nrendered 0.81 of curated terms in English script; this is also the shortest lecture (4m30s), so its\nhigh raw rendering may reflect length as well as content.\n   Second, English-script rendering is a useful readability proxy for Korean–English medical\nlectures, but it is not semantic faithfulness. A high rendering rate can coexist with wrong English\nterms (Section 6.3), so script rendering and medical meaning must be measured separately.\n   Third, post-ASR rewriting can improve readability while adding paraphrase, compression,\nand faithfulness risks, especially when raw ASR is already close to the reference. The cross-\ninput comparison suggests that some polarity failures were post-processing-associated, whereas\nbroader semantic drift was more input-sensitive.\n   Fourth, these findings should not be read as evidence that all domain-aware post-processing\nintroduces semantic drift. AI_LectureNote is a readability-oriented LLM rewriting pipeline\nrather than a constrained term-normalization system; the diagnostic point is that script-\nrendering gains and semantic faithfulness should be evaluated separately.\n\n8. Limitations\nThis retrospective pilot bounds every claim above; we make no benchmark, population-rate,\neducational, or clinical claim.\n  • Scale and confounding. Four lectures only. Speaker, topic, lecture length, and reference\n     style remain confounded, even after adding a second cdh lecture.\n  • Annotation provenance and evaluator overlap. References and labels were created\n     via single-pass annotation by the system developers (single author-annotator) with no sec-\n\n                                                9\n\f    ond pass, independent replication, adjudication, or inter-annotator agreement. Further-\n    more, references are lightly cleaned study transcripts rather than gold-standard verbatim\n    transcripts.\n  • Polarity concentration. Polarity failures concentrate in diuretics_01, so polarity\n    comparisons are illustrative rather than robust rate estimates.\n  • Implementation choices. Condition 5 is a diagnostic control, not an optimized modern-\n    STT post-processor; the gpt-4o conditions use 3-minute non-overlapping chunks and one\n    minimal prompt, and the whisper-1 condition is a 2026 rerun rather than a 2023 snapshot.\n  • Metric scope. English-script rendering is recall-like and script-only; it does not measure\n    term correctness or hallucinated terms except through missed reference terms.\n  • Korean-phonetic diagnostic counts. The Korean-phonetic counts are diagnostic lower-\n    bound counts based on a machine-assisted list of observed phonetic variants; the phonetic\n    variant lists were not exhaustively verified.\n\n9. Conclusion\nAcross four author-recorded lectures, AI_LectureNote-style post-processing improved English-\nscript rendering on both input paths, but these readability gains coexisted with semantic drift\nand polarity failures. The cross-input control suggested that polarity failures were more stable\nacross raw front-ends than general semantic drift, whose affected sentences shifted with the\ninput ASR. The central methodological takeaway is that surface distance, term-script render-\ning, chunk-level consistency, and medical-meaning preservation should be evaluated separately.\nFuture work should test more constrained alternatives, such as span-level glossary replacement,\nverifier-backed correction, or constrained rewriting.\n\n10. Reproducibility / Data and Code Availability\nFrom the evaluation_paper/ directory, all tables and figures regenerate with python\nanalysis/run_all.py. Source files are organized as (paths relative to evaluation_paper/):\n   • References\n      data/<lecture>/reference.txt\n   • Semantic labels\n      annotations/<lecture>/semantic_review.csv\n   • Condition-5 semantic labels\n      annotations/<lecture>/semantic_review_gpt4o_ailn_post.csv\n   • Polarity labels\n      annotations/<lecture>/polarity_review.csv\n   • Domain terms\n      annotations/<lecture>/domain_terms.csv\n   • Condition manifest\n      manifest/condition_manifest.csv\n   The condition manifest records model names, API dates, prompt text, and the condition-5\npipeline description.\n   Code, speaker-coded evaluation transcripts, references, annotation files, and generated tables/\nfigures are released in the public repository: https://github.com/boyskier/ailecturenote-\nretrospective-pilot. Where audio is included, it is released with explicit author-speaker consent\nfor research reproducibility; because the audio contains identifiable voices, it should not be\ntreated as anonymized.\n\n\n\n\n                                               10\n\fAcknowledgements\nWe thank Professor Hogun Park for supervising the 2024 CO-Deep Learning student project\nthat laid the foundation for this work.\n\nAppendix A. Supplementary figures\nThe four main figures appear inline (Figure 1, Section 4.1; Figure 2, Section 6.2; Figure 3 and\nFigure 4, Section 6.3). The following supplementary figures provide per-lecture detail and are\nreproduced by python analysis/run_all.py:\n   • Figure S1 (figures/fig2_cer_wer.png) — per-lecture CER (primary) and WER\n     (secondary) for all five conditions, showing the anthrax_01 and anticancerdrugs_02\n     divergence where raw whisper-1 is clean but post-processing raises CER (Section 6.1).\n   • Figure S2 (figures/fig1_english_script_rate.png) — English-script rendering rate\n     by condition and lecture, the per-lecture detail behind the headline trade-off in Figure 2\n     (Section 6.2).\n   • Figures S3a–d (figures/fig3_chunk_<lecture>.png) — per-3-minute-chunk English\n     vs. Korean-phonetic counts for raw and prompted gpt-4o, one panel per lecture\n     (acuteinflammation_02, anthrax_01, anticancerdrugs_02, diuretics_01), illustrating\n     the chunk-level script instability (Section 6.2).\n\nAppendix B. Illustrative errors\nAppendix B lists illustrative author-reviewed errors.         The examples are drawn from\ntable7_semantic_drift_examples.csv. Examples include propagated substitutions such\nas lymphocyte → “lipocyte” and tissue edema → “tissue adenoma”; introduced or post-\nprocessing-associated polarity/substitution errors such as hypercalcemia → “hypercalciuria”\nand hypokalemia-prevention → “hyperkalemia-prevention”; and additions such as an unmen-\ntioned “ibuprofen” in the ototoxicity discussion. Condition 5 also produced a concept error in\nanticancerdrugs_02, conflating antimetabolites with alkylating agents.\n   For balance, post-processing also corrected some upstream errors in anthrax_01, including\nrestoring whisper-1’s “Annihilation” to “Inhalation”, preserving the 90–95% / 20% mortality\nfigures, and restoring the PA/EF/LF abbreviations in English. Thus, the examples illustrate\nmixed effects of readability-oriented rewriting rather than a one-directional degradation.\n\n\n\nReferences\n  • Adedeji, A., Joshi, S., & Doohan, B. (2024). The Sound of Healthcare: Improving Medical\n    Transcription ASR Accuracy with Large Language Models. arXiv:2402.07658.\n  • Adedeji, A., Sanni, M., Ayodele, E., Joshi, S., & Olatunji, T. (2025). The Multi-\n    cultural Medical Assistant: Can LLMs Improve Medical ASR Errors Across Borders?\n    arXiv:2501.15310.\n  • Chapman, W. W., Bridewell, W., Hanbury, P., Cooper, G. F., & Buchanan, B. G. (2001).\n    A simple algorithm for identifying negated findings and diseases in discharge summaries.\n    Journal of Biomedical Informatics, 34(5), 301–310. doi:10.1006/jbin.2001.1029.\n  • Ma, R., Qian, M., Manakul, P., Gales, M., & Knill, K. (2023). Can Generative Large\n    Language Models Perform ASR Error Correction? arXiv:2307.04172.\n  • OpenAI. (2025). Speech to text. OpenAI API documentation. Accessed 2026-06-27.\n    https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/speech-to-text\n  • Paik, G., Kim, Y., Lee, S., Ahn, S., & Kim, C. (2025). HiKE: Hierarchical Evaluation\n\n\n                                              11\n\f  Framework for Korean–English Code-Switching Speech Recognition. arXiv:2509.24613.\n• Peng, Y., Wang, X., Lu, L., Bagheri, M., Summers, R. M., & Lu, Z. (2017). Neg-\n  Bio: a high-performance tool for negation and uncertainty detection in radiology reports.\n  arXiv:1712.05898.\n• Radford, A., Kim, J. W., Xu, T., Brockman, G., McLeavey, C., & Sutskever, I.\n  (2023). Robust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision (Whisper). Proceed-\n  ings of the 40th International Conference on Machine Learning, PMLR 202:28492–28518.\n  arXiv:2212.04356.\n• Sitaram, S., Chandu, K. R., Rallabandi, S. K., & Black, A. W. (2019). A survey of\n  code-switched speech and language processing. arXiv:1904.00784.\n• Sudo, Y., Shakeel, M., Fukumoto, Y., Peng, Y., & Watanabe, S. (20